bru-lang/language.content:
Language Design


A Bru file is made up of blocks.
There are three kinds of blocks
- Dictionary block
- Text blocks
- Array blocks

Dictionary block

A dictionary block contains of a set of key value pairs. 
```bash
get {
  url: https://api.textlocal.in/send
}

headers {
  content-type: application/json
  Authorization: Bearer 123
  ~transaction-id: {{transactionId}}
}
```
Any key in the dictionary block can be prefixed with `~` to indicate that it is disabled.

Text block

A text block is a set of lines
```bash
body {
  {
    "hello": "world"
  }
}

tests {
  expect(res.status).to.equal(200);
}
```

Array block

An array block is a list of strings
```bash
vars:secret [
  access_key,
  access_secret,
  ~transactionId
]
```
Any key in the array block can be prefixed with `~` to indicate that it is disabled.

bru-lang/samples.content:
Samples


Here are a few sample Bru files.

GET

```bash
get {
  url: https://api.github.com/users/usebruno
}
```

GET with headers

```bash
get {
  url: https://api.textlocal.in/send?apiKey=secret&numbers=9988776655&message=hello
}

headers {
  content-type: application/json
  Authorization: Bearer topsecret
}
```

POST with body

```bash
post {
  url: https://api.textlocal.in/send
}

body {
  {
    "apiKey": "secret",
    "numbers": "9988776655",
    "message": "Woof! lets play with some apis"
  }
}

headers {
  content-type: application/json
  Authorization: Bearer topsecret
}
```

Scripting

```bash
post {
  url: https://api.textlocal.in/login
}

body {
  {
    "username": "johnnash",
    "password": "governingdynamics"
  }
}

script:post-response {
  bru.setVar("token", res.body.token);
}
```

Testing

```bash
post {
  url: https://api.textlocal.in/login
}

body {
  {
    "username": "johnnash",
    "password": "governingdynamics"
  }
}

tests {
  test("should be able to login", function() {
    expect(res.status).to.equal(201);
  });

  test("should receive the token", function() {
    expect(res.body.token).to.be.a('string');
  });
}
```

bru-lang/tag-reference.content:
Bru Tag Reference


meta

Store metadata about your request
```bash
meta {
  name: Get users,
  type: http
  seq: 1
}
```

The `seq` is used to store the sequence number. This decides the sort position of your request in the UI.
The `type` can be either `http` or `graphql`

get


Make a `GET` http call
```bash
get {
  url: https://api.github.com/users/usebruno
}
```
post


Make a `POST` http call
```bash
post {
  url: https://api.github.com/users/usebruno
}
```
put


Make a `PUT` http call
```bash
put {
  url: https://api.github.com/users/usebruno
}
```
delete


Make a `DELETE` http call
```bash
delete {
  url: https://api.github.com/users/usebruno
}
```
options


Make a get `OPTIONS` call
```bash
options {
  url: https://api.github.com/users/usebruno
}
```
trace


Make a `TRACE` http call
```bash
trace {
  url: https://api.github.com/users/usebruno
}
```
connect


Make a `CONNECT` http call
```bash
connect {
  url: https://api.github.com/users/usebruno
}
```
head


Make a `HEAD` http call
```bash
head {
  url: https://api.github.com/users/usebruno
}
```
query


The request query params
```bash
get {
  url: https://api.textlocal.in/send?apiKey=secret&numbers=9988776655&message=hello
}

query {
  apiKey: secret
  numbers: 9988776655
  message: hello
}
```
headers


The request query headers
```bash
get {
  url: https://api.textlocal.in/send?apiKey=secret&numbers=9988776655&message=hello
}

headers {
  content-type: application/json
  Authorization: Bearer topsecret
}
```

body

The request body (defaults to json)
```bash
body {
  {
    username: 'john',
    password: 'governingdynamics'
  }
}
```
body:text

The request body as text
```bash
body:text {
  This is a text body
}
```
body:xml

The request body as xml
```bash
body:xml {

    John
    30

}
```
body:form-urlencoded

The request body as form-urlencoded
```bash
body:form-urlencoded {
  apikey: secret
  numbers: +91998877665
  ~message: hello
}
```
body:multipart-form

The request body as multipart-form
```bash
body:multipart-form {
  apikey: secret
  numbers: +91998877665
  ~message: hello
}
```
body:graphql

The request body as graphql
```bash
body:graphql {
  {
    launchesPast {
      launch_site {
        site_name
      }
      launch_success
    }
  }
}
```
body:graphql:vars

The request body as graphql vars
```bash
body:graphql:vars {
  {
    "limit": 5
  }
}
```
script:pre-request

The request body as pre-request
```bash
script:pre-request {
  req.setHeader("Authorization", "{{token}}");
}
```
script:post-response

The request body as post-response
```bash
script:post-response {
  bru.setVar("token", res.body.token);
}
```
test

The tests
```bash
body:test {
  expect(res.status).to.equal(200);
}
```

scripting/external-libraries.content:
External Libraries


Bruno supports loading any npm module to use in your scripting workflows.

You need to add a `package.json` file where your collection is stored.
```js
{
  "name": "github-rest-api-collection",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "index.js",
  "homepage": "https://github.com/usebruno/github-rest-api-collection#readme",
  "dependencies": {
    "@faker-js/faker": "8.3.1"
  }
}
```

And then run npm install inside your collection folder
```bash
npm install
```

And then you can require the node module in your script as usual.
**Example:**
```js
const { faker } = require('@faker-js/faker');

const randomName = faker.name.fullName();
const randomEmail = faker.internet.email();

req.setBody({
  name: randomName,
  email: randomEmail
});
```

scripting/sync-requests.content:
Sync requests


You can make synchronous requests in your pre/post scripts. By synchronous, we mean that you can await a request in your scripting code.

Below is an inbuilt example of using `axios` library to
```js
const axios = require("axios");

const response = await axios.get("https://api.github.com/users/usebruno");

bru.setVar("avatarUrl", response.data.avatar_url);
```

